In a simulation study, a small number of design factors are specified. This article covers six factors: covariate prevalence (

p

), that is, the proportion of subjects who are female, sample size (N), treatment effect (β1), covariate effect (β2), survival pattern (τ), and attrition rate (r). The attrition rate is defined as the proportion of subjects who leave the study between any two adjacent time points due to unforeseen reasons other than event occurrence. The factors and their levels are summarized in Table 1.

To assess the strategies in greater detail, we first consider the results for a trial with no treatment effect (
O R
(
β
1
) = 1
). The Type I error rates are almost similar in all the strategies and they are close to their nominal level of 5% within each covariate effect. We then focus on the results obtained if the treatment is not absent (
O R
(
β
1
) > 1
). With the prespecified strategy, the power is greater than with the unadjusted strategy within each treatment and covariate effect. The difference in power between these two strategies is somewhat higher for a larger covariate effect. Conversely, power with the significant-predictor strategy only slightly increases as compared to the unadjusted one when the covariate effect is small. As the covariate effect grows, so does the increase in power. It is evident that the difference between the prespecified and the significant-predictor strategies in estimating the treatment effect is directly related to the strength of the covariate effect. In other words, the larger the covariate effect, the smaller the difference. The power compared with no adjustment does not change at all or only negligibly when the significant-imbalance strategy is used. This strategy also results in a minor decrease in the power of the simulation condition with small treatment and covariate effects. A potential reduction in sample size is observed with a large covariate effect when the prespecified and significant-predictor strategies are used. For a smaller covariate effect, the prespecified strategy yields much smaller reductions and the significant-predictor strategy only slightly reduces the sample size. Since the significant-imbalance strategy mainly yields similar results to the unadjusted analysis, it generally results in minor or negligible reductions.

To address the issue of whether strategy performances differ when different attrition rates are used, the results corresponding to various attrition rates (
