r = 0.25
), no subjects are found in the last time period for some of the generated data sets, so no parameter estimates are given for these data sets. Since there are so few of these data sets (in this study, at most 34 of 10,000 data sets), they are not included in the simulated data sets.

A simulation shows the power to detect the effect of the treatment is estimated at 0.50 in a model without the covariate, and estimated at 0.52 if controlling for the effect of the wife’s education level. Since the sample size of 170 is not sufficient and consequently results in an underpowered study, we consider a higher value for the sample size which could obtain sufficient power. If we have a trial with 350 subjects, then this gives us 82% power to detect the same difference in an unadjusted model, and 84% in the adjusted model. This gain in power can also be expressed by the RSS (3.5

%

). It means that we can decrease the sample size to 338 and detect the effect of the treatment with 82% power. If the effect of the covariate was estimated to be much larger, for instance equal to −1.39, then we would have 71% unadjusted power to detect the same treatment effect and the prespecified strategy would result in 77% power and this would result in an 11.2% reduction in sample size.

We have discussed the use of covariate adjustment strategies in RCTs with continuous-time survival endpoints analysed with Cox proportional hazard models (Hernandez et al., 2006). From our results, the effect of the covariate adjustment also applies to trials with discrete-time survival endpoints, as are common in the social and behavioral sciences. In addition, Hernandez et al. (2006) only consider a decreasing hazard probability function (
τ
< 1
). In our study, the covariate adjustment strategies are also investigated for the Weibull survival function with the risk of event occurrence either increasing over time (
τ
> 1
) or remaining constant (
τ
= 1
).
